<div id="Idea_3008"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/3008-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_3008">criteria for federal employee appraisals&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4351-4049">ctb14</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">7 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Criteria for federal employee performance appraisals should be set by career managers and executives, not political appointees.  It is too easy for a president and political appointees to use discretion under the law to frustrate congressional intent, if  they can use the lever of performance appraisals to get federal employees to focus on an ideological agenda, versus execution of the law that is faithful to congressional intent.  The bureaucracy needs to be depoliticized.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_3008" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_3008', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2251&topicID=3008')">Comments (1)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_3008"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2251">Performance Appraisal</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_3008"></div>
