<div id="Idea_2933"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/2933-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_2933">Bar Code (and Inventory, Annually) Every Object Owned by The Federal Government&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4200-4049">david.wenbert</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">8 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Contemporary "3-D" barcode technology can encode significant amounts of information on inventory control decals (i.e. identifying a specific custodial official with cognizance over the object), but even first generation serial/sequential code tags could rapidly bring some semblance of control to the federal tangible assets database.</div>
